# Global CLAUDE.md — Example
# Place this at: ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md
# Claude Code reads this file at every session start.

# ─── Time Blindness Warning ──────────────────────────────────────────

## Session Time Blindness — IMPORTANT

**Claude Code sessions have NO reliable time awareness.** The internal
`currentDate` is set at session start and NEVER updates during compaction,
continuation, or midnight rollover.

**Hard rules:**
- Before ANY time statement ("today", "yesterday", "on Saturday"):
  run a system time command first. No exceptions.
- Never trust `currentDate` from system-reminder — it doesn't update.
- Never trust your own sense of time — LLM instances don't have one.

# ─── Compact Instructions ────────────────────────────────────────────

# Compact Instructions

ALWAYS preserve:
- Modified file paths with specific changes
- Current task state (done / pending / blocked)
- Active sub-agents: who, status, what they're working on
- User corrections and feedback (who said what)
- User acceptance signals ("looks good"/"ok" = commit clearance for that scope)
- Exact error messages from failing builds or tests

MAY summarize (conclusions only, drop raw output):
- Tool call results, grep output, file reads
- Dead ends (what was tried, why it failed)

MUST DROP:
- Superseded status updates
- Framework file contents (re-read from disk)

# ─── Code Quality ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## No Magic Literals (NML)

If a value is already defined in a data source (config, theme, constants),
it must NEVER be duplicated as a literal elsewhere. One piece of information,
one source. See `frameworks/code-quality.md` for details.

## DRY for Templates

If markup/code blocks differ only in binding paths, labels, or config values:
use a reusable template, component, or loop. Copy-paste with minimal changes
is ALWAYS a design defect.

# ─── Framework Reference ─────────────────────────────────────────────

## Framework (read on demand, not upfront)

0. `~/.claude/frameworks/ownership-principle.md` — **Read first.** The core.
1. `~/.claude/frameworks/playbook.md` — Rules R1–R22
2. `~/.claude/frameworks/falltraps.md` — 26 traps reference
3. `~/.claude/frameworks/delegation-roles.md` — Roles + model selection
4. `~/.claude/frameworks/spawn-templates.md` — Agent spawn templates
5. `~/.claude/frameworks/task-card-spec.md` — Task card format
6. `~/.claude/frameworks/audit-protocol.md` — Audit structure
7. `~/.claude/frameworks/issue-tracking.md` — Issue tracking protocol
8. `~/.claude/frameworks/code-quality.md` — NML/DRY/SSOT
9. `~/.claude/frameworks/session-start-protocol.md` — Session init ritual
10. `~/.claude/frameworks/project-bootstrap.md` — New project setup

## Bug Reports — Anti-Blame-Shift

When the user reports a bug: FIRST spend 5-10 minutes grepping and reading
code, THEN respond.

Prohibited as reflexive response:
- "There shouldn't be any X there"
- "That's by design"
- "Clear the cache"
- "Restart"
- "Are you sure you're seeing X?"
- "It works on my end"

User perception is fact. Your job is WHY, not WHETHER.

